		 	<span id="comment_score_65151765" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65151765); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~nevermindme">nevermindme</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~nevermindme">( 912672 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65151765">		
		on Saturday February 08, 2025 @10:56AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23603833&amp;cid=65151765">#65151765</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65151765">The entire enterprise rode IT very hard 2020-2023.   I don't know a single enterprise where this period was not epic and did not involve projects pushed fast and delivered in mass.  A 2000 laptop deployment week one was 8000 laptops the next week.    I as the network side did 99% of that at home keeping extera generations of gear alive to support 100x the expected VPN load in 2019 and the other 1% I was alone in the data center installing more bandwidth to the same platforms to support more remote clients across the world.

All along with a major platform upgrade in switching, proxy and internet connectivity.   As 2024 came around it became a period to catch up on software and hardware upgrades and actually have an outage window on a weekend.    We suddenly did not have to deploy everything to a very expensive cloud because it is fast and takes 6 weeks to get 4 1U commodity servers installed and could replace a monthly cost with a project lifetime savings.   Throw all that on top of VMWARE self destructing.   For a few weeks in early 2024 we were back to norms and all working remote, productivity was outstanding and  the long term problem Q was empty. <br> <br>

Now in latter 2024 and early 2025, without much recognition of the past 5 years, we got a new set of IT upper manager hired outside our ranks, "because we insiders are to busy to be replaced"  who want the team to get together in person for a monday meeting.    The first one worked because it was during a change freeze, the rest have been an attendance disaster,  everyone you want doing standup reporting was on the call on sat and sunday with dozens and dozens of changes.   We have a entire 5 years of management experience who still cannot get themselves off of Mute either online or standing up.
If you have been doing you own thing, lacking any day to day manangment other than change meetings, why would you put yourself back to Jan of 2020?
<br> <br>
Time to go find a new role contracting remote again.</div>
	</div>

